Midgaard's self-understanding centers on the First Stone Accord's principle that all roads must return to a watched square. The Magistrate Ledgerhouse teaches that order created prosperity and minimizes moral compromise in its archive records. Guard Command elevates siege-memory and treats legal ambiguity as wartime pragmatism. The Lantern Registry preserves route names, dates, and civic truth — becoming accidental custodians of inconvenient facts. Three civic oaths still govern public life: Oath of Light (no ward unlit, no traveler uncounted), Oath of Stone (no judgment hidden, no sentence unrecorded), Oath of Bread (no levy taken that cannot be borne). These oaths are idealized and frequently violated; the gap between them and institutional practice is the primary source of Midgaard's internal political friction. The Continuity faction holds the archive access levers; the Reckoning faction holds the moral argument. The Unindexed Years — ledger gaps between late Violet Compact and early Ash-and-Iron period — are the contested evidence: Continuity says wartime triage, Reckoning says deliberate erasure of condemned-debtor transfer records.

